article.description:
Michael Redd scored 30 points and Dan Gadzuric
added a season-high 16 to help the Milwaukee Bucks beat the Orlando
Magic 104-84 on Saturday night.
article.headline: Redd drops 30, Bucks beat Magic handily
article.linkText: Redd drops 30, Bucks beat Magic handily
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Dan Gadzuric had a lot of fun at the Orlando Magic's expense. Gadzuric scored nine straight points for Milwaukee during a key fourth-quarter stretch and had 14 of his season-high 16 points in the period to help the Bucks beat the Magic 104-84 on Saturday night. "It was a lot of fun," Gadzuric said. "Everybody was doing what they needed to do." Michael Redd led Milwaukee with 30 points. He also had five assists and three rebounds for the Bucks, who shot 56.6 percent (43-for-76) from the field. After Orlando rookie Travis Diener's 3-pointer cut Milwaukee's lead to five at 78-73 with 7:55 left, Gadzuric scored the Bucks' next nine points. "They were just finding me," Gadzuric said. "I was just trying to find an open space and trying to create. They saw me and all I had to do was finish." Gadzuric, who averages 3.6 points per game and had a total of 13 points in his last three games, capped his scoring spree with an alley-oop dunk that gave Milwaukee an 89-75 lead with 5:24 left. "He finished around the paint, defensively he was getting rebounds and he covered the pick and roll well," Milwaukee coach Terry Stotts said. "There wasn't a thing I didn't like." Jameer Nelson led Orlando, playing without Steve Francis (bruised chest) for the second straight game, with 20 points. "They found Gadzuric," Nelson said. "Michael Redd did a good job of spotting up. But the biggest thing was Gadzuric. He had 16 points." DeShawn Stevenson scored 15 points, and Diener, a former Marquette star who made his NBA debut Dec. 2, was 5-for-6 from the field and finished with 14 points. "These are his baskets," Orlando coach Brian Hill said. "I was hoping we'd get something like that from him. I was really happy for him to see him do that in front of his hometown fans." But Diener didn't see it that way. "It really doesn't mean much," he said. "If we would have won and I would have had zero points it would be better than losing." The Magic concluded their four-game trip with a 1-3 record.

Game notes
The Bucks have won 13 of the last 14 games against the Magic at the Bradley Center. Orlando has lost three straight games and Milwaukee has won three in a row. ... Bobby Simmons and Joe Smith were inactive for Milwaukee. Simmons has a sprained right ankle and Smith has pain in his left knee. ... The Bucks are 7-1 against Eastern Conference teams. ... Gadzuric's career high is 22 points.
